name: Dimethyl terephthalate
Reason: The basic unit for comparison will be benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 °C. The dimethyl terephthalate molecule has two ester groups linked to a benzene ring and an additional benzene ring. Each ester group typically increases the melting point because of the polar carbonyl group and additional intermolecular forces, such as dipole-dipole interactions. Ester groups can add approximately +40 to +50 °C per ester group to the melting point of a benzene ring. Furthermore, the second benzene ring contributes additional rigidity and intermolecular interactions through π-π stacking, which can raise the melting point by additional +20 °C. This gives the approximate contributions as follows: benzene melting point (5.5 °C), plus two ester groups (2 * +45 °C = +90 °C), plus the additional rigidity and interactions from the second benzene ring (+20 °C).
